Well. it's... It's a
magnificent stone.

4
00:00:18.219 --> 00:00:20.730
They put it up this morning.

5
00:00:20.754 --> 00:00:22.265
Well...

6
00:00:22.289 --> 00:00:24.649
It's just a magnificent stone.

7
00:00:25.792 --> 00:00:27.292
Jerry?

8
00:00:31.632 --> 00:00:32.632
George.

9
00:00:34.368 --> 00:00:36.279
we'll leave you alone with her.

10
00:00:36.303 --> 00:00:37.780
What?

11
00:00:37.804 --> 00:00:39.949
I'm sure there are
things you'd like to say.

12
00:00:39.973 --> 00:00:42.619
No. I-I'm... I'm good.

13
00:00:42.643 --> 00:00:45.188
Really. Jerry?

14
00:00:45.212 --> 00:00:46.645
Jerry?

15
00:01:05.433 --> 00:01:07.244
Thank you. no.

16
00:01:07.268 --> 00:01:11.481
And then right after the.
uh... The All-Star break we...

17
00:01:11.505 --> 00:01:13.605
We just swept the Orioles.

18
00:01:15.642 --> 00:01:17.921
Four games.

19
00:01:17.945 --> 00:01:19.878
In Baltimore.

20
00:01:22.416 --> 00:01:24.015
So...

21
00:01:27.554 --> 00:01:28.532
[♪♪♪]

22
00:01:28.556 --> 00:01:29.999
[DOOR OPENS]

23
00:01:30.023 --> 00:01:31.535
GEORGE: Boy. that was awkward.

24
00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:33.002
I don't mind the cemetery.

25
00:01:33.026 --> 00:01:35.705
In fact. now I see
why people like golf.

26
00:01:35.729 --> 00:01:38.608
It's just nice to be outside
in a well-landscaped area.

27
00:01:38.632 --> 00:01:41.511
What were you saying to the
Rosses over there anyway?

28
00:01:41.535 --> 00:01:43.046
Oh. man. I don't know.

29
00:01:43.070 --> 00:01:46.450
I-I told 'em. "Her death takes
place in the shadow of new life.

30
00:01:46.474 --> 00:01:49.453
She's not really dead if we
find a way to remember her."

31
00:01:49.477 --> 00:01:50.454
What is that?

32
00:01:50.478 --> 00:01:51.721
<i>Star Trek II.</i>

33
00:01:51.745 --> 00:01:53.723
<i>Wrath of Khan.</i>

34
00:01:53.747 --> 00:01:56.193
Right. Kramer and
I saw it last night.

35
00:01:56.217 --> 00:01:58.562
Spock dies. They wrap him
up in a towel and they shoot him

36
00:01:58.586 --> 00:02:02.699
out the bowels of the ship
in that big sunglasses case.

37
00:02:02.723 --> 00:02:06.203
It was a hell of a
thing when Spock died.

38
00:02:06.227 --> 00:02:08.393
Yeah.

39
00:02:11.565 --> 00:02:14.611
Well. anyway. the. uh...

40
00:02:14.635 --> 00:02:15.645
The stone is up.

41
00:02:15.669 --> 00:02:17.380
Paid my respects.

42
00:02:17.404 --> 00:02:19.749
I guess that's it. huh?

43
00:02:19.773 --> 00:02:21.050
So it's over?

44
00:02:21.074 --> 00:02:24.053
I have mourned for three long
months. summer months too.

45
00:02:24.077 --> 00:02:26.423
Anybody could grieve in January.

46
00:02:26.447 --> 00:02:29.292
It's... It's time for George
to start being George again.

47
00:02:29.316 --> 00:02:31.294
All right. So. uh. let's
do something later.

48
00:02:31.318 --> 00:02:32.695
How about a movie? Yes!

49
00:02:32.719 --> 00:02:35.732
Nothing says "George"
like a movie. Ah. movie?

50
00:02:35.756 --> 00:02:36.933
Yeah. you in?

51
00:02:36.957 --> 00:02:38.968
No. no. no. I can't. I
got my martial arts class.

52
00:02:38.992 --> 00:02:40.992
Well. George is
going to the movie!

53
00:02:42.429 --> 00:02:44.107
So how's your
karate class going?

54
00:02:44.131 --> 00:02:46.743
"Ka-ra-tay." Jerry. "ka-ra-tay."

55
00:02:46.767 --> 00:02:49.346
It's the lifetime pursuit
of balance and harmony.

56
00:02:49.370 --> 00:02:51.181
But with punching and kicking.

57
00:02:51.205 --> 00:02:52.982
Jerry.

58
00:02:53.006 --> 00:02:55.084
Karate is not here.

59
00:02:55.108 --> 00:02:56.486
It's here.

60
00:02:56.510 --> 00:02:58.255
And here.

61
00:02:58.279 --> 00:03:00.290
And here.

62
00:03:00.314 --> 00:03:03.126
All right. I gotta go to the
airport and pick up Elaine.

63
00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:04.794
What. she's been away?

64
00:03:04.818 --> 00:03:07.797
She's been in
Mexico for six weeks.

65
00:03:07.821 --> 00:03:08.998
I think you're wrong.

66
00:03:09.022 --> 00:03:12.001
We just went to the
fireworks the other day.

67
00:03:12.025 --> 00:03:14.125
That was July 4th.

68
00:03:18.632 --> 00:03:19.809
All right. I'm outta here.

69
00:03:19.833 --> 00:03:21.778
And when I get back. I
don't wanna see you here.

70
00:03:21.802 --> 00:03:24.080
Here. or here.

71
00:03:24.104 --> 00:03:26.949
[♪♪♪]

72
00:03:26.973 --> 00:03:28.552
ELAINE: It was unbelievable.

73
00:03:28.576 --> 00:03:33.122
Six weeks of traveling through
Mexico. all on Peterman's peso.

74
00:03:33.146 --> 00:03:35.659
Wow. so did you get any
good ideas for the catalogue?

75
00:03:35.683 --> 00:03:37.627
Oh. tons. Anything
you couldn't have gotten

76
00:03:37.651 --> 00:03:40.797
tearing open a bag of Doritos
and watching<i> Viva Zapata?</i>

77
00:03:40.821 --> 00:03:41.998
[CHUCKLES]

78
00:03:42.022 --> 00:03:44.167
You don't respect
my work at all. do you?

79
00:03:44.191 --> 00:03:45.168
No. I don't.

80
00:03:45.192 --> 00:03:46.469
No.

81
00:03:46.493 --> 00:03:49.472
So. what's been going
on around this dump?

82
00:03:49.496 --> 00:03:51.140
How's your fiancée?

83
00:03:51.164 --> 00:03:52.664
My what?

84
00:03:53.934 --> 00:03:57.214
Jeannie? Your fiancée?

85
00:03:57.238 --> 00:04:00.183
Oh. yeah. That.

86
00:04:00.207 --> 00:04:01.651
Well...

87
00:04:01.675 --> 00:04:04.521
All right. Spill it. Jerome.

88
00:04:04.545 --> 00:04:06.356
There's really not
that much to tell.

89
00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:08.692
<i>About a month ago we
were here having lunch.</i>

90
00:04:08.716 --> 00:04:10.993
<i>and all of a sudden
we both just blurted out:</i>

91
00:04:11.017 --> 00:04:13.697
BOTH: I hate you.

92
00:04:13.721 --> 00:04:15.287
See ya. See ya.

93
00:04:17.057 --> 00:04:19.669
<i>It was unprecedented.
I mean. it was the first</i>

94
00:04:19.693 --> 00:04:22.405
<i>truly mutual breakup
in relationship history.</i>

95
00:04:22.429 --> 00:04:25.074
No rejection. no
guilt. no remorse.

96
00:04:25.098 --> 00:04:26.676
You've never felt remorse.

97
00:04:26.700 --> 00:04:29.379
I know. I feel bad about that.

98
00:04:29.403 --> 00:04:32.349
I bet your parents
were upset. huh? Eh.

99
00:04:32.373 --> 00:04:34.917
You haven't told 'em
yet. have you? No.

100
00:04:34.941 --> 00:04:37.520
[♪♪♪]

101
00:04:37.544 --> 00:04:40.022
"So I pressed
through the rushes.

102
00:04:40.046 --> 00:04:44.761
There below me. the shimmering
waters of Lake Victoria."

103
00:04:44.785 --> 00:04:47.530
Oh. for the love of God. man.

104
00:04:47.554 --> 00:04:50.400
Just tell me what
the product is.

105
00:04:50.424 --> 00:04:52.935
It's a... washcloth.

106
00:04:52.959 --> 00:04:56.038
No washcloths.

107
00:04:56.062 --> 00:04:58.275
Well. Mr. Peterman.

108
00:04:58.299 --> 00:05:01.043
I've got a really
good idea for a hat.

109
00:05:01.067 --> 00:05:06.249
Oh. my neck is one
gargantuan monkey fist.

110
00:05:06.273 --> 00:05:08.752
It combines the
spirit of old Mexico

111
00:05:08.776 --> 00:05:12.889
with a little big-city panache.

112
00:05:12.913 --> 00:05:15.659
I like to call it the
"urban sombrero."

113
00:05:15.683 --> 00:05:16.660
No. no.

114
00:05:16.684 --> 00:05:18.583
No pears.

115
00:05:20.788 --> 00:05:21.765
Mr. Peterman?

116
00:05:21.789 --> 00:05:24.233
No apples.

117
00:05:24.257 --> 00:05:26.670
ELAINE: Um?

118
00:05:26.694 --> 00:05:29.972
Where's my pineapple?

119
00:05:29.996 --> 00:05:31.708
Are you okay. Mr. Peterman?

120
00:05:31.732 --> 00:05:36.179
Yes. yes. go on. Go on. Go on.

121
00:05:36.203 --> 00:05:40.750
Well. see. it's
businessmen taking siestas.

122
00:05:40.774 --> 00:05:42.084
[GROANING]

123
00:05:42.108 --> 00:05:45.322
You know. it's the. uh...
It's the urban sombrero.

124
00:05:45.346 --> 00:05:47.757
Mr. Peterman?

125
00:05:47.781 --> 00:05:49.125
[♪♪♪]

126
00:05:49.149 --> 00:05:50.893
Hey. Jerry. I'm
feeling somethin'.

127
00:05:50.917 --> 00:05:52.662
somethin' I haven't
felt for a long time.

128
00:05:52.686 --> 00:05:54.798
Pride? No.

129
00:05:54.822 --> 00:05:57.801
Autonomy. complete
and total autonomy.

130
00:05:57.825 --> 00:05:59.636
Well. you're your own boss now.

131
00:05:59.660 --> 00:06:00.837
I wanna go to a tractor pull.

132
00:06:00.861 --> 00:06:01.838
Go ahead.

133
00:06:01.862 --> 00:06:03.072
I am staying out all night.

134
00:06:03.096 --> 00:06:04.607
Who's stopping you?

135
00:06:04.631 --> 00:06:06.209
I wanna bite into a
big hunk of cheese.

136
00:06:06.233 --> 00:06:08.745
just bite into it
like it's an apple.

137
00:06:08.769 --> 00:06:10.347
Whatever.

138
00:06:10.371 --> 00:06:11.348
JERRY: Oh. God.

139
00:06:11.372 --> 00:06:12.449
GEORGE: What?

140
00:06:12.473 --> 00:06:13.450
It's Dolores.

141
00:06:13.474 --> 00:06:14.517
Who?

142
00:06:14.541 --> 00:06:16.720
Mulva.

143
00:06:16.744 --> 00:06:18.020
Jerry. hi.

144
00:06:18.044 --> 00:06:19.356
Hi. Dolores.

145
00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:20.990
George. you remember Dolores.

146
00:06:21.014 --> 00:06:21.991
Dolores.

147
00:06:22.015 --> 00:06:22.992
Hi.

148
00:06:23.016 --> 00:06:24.627
I heard you got engaged.

149
00:06:24.651 --> 00:06:26.028
Yes. Dolores. I did.

150
00:06:26.052 --> 00:06:28.231
It didn't work out.
though. Dolores.

151
00:06:28.255 --> 00:06:29.733
Oh. that's too bad.

152
00:06:29.757 --> 00:06:33.135
You know. we should
get together some time.

153
00:06:33.159 --> 00:06:34.136
See ya.

154
00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:35.137
See ya.

155
00:06:35.161 --> 00:06:37.039
Bye. Dolores.

156
00:06:37.063 --> 00:06:39.141
I thought Mulva hated you.

157
00:06:39.165 --> 00:06:40.910
Yeah. so did I.

158
00:06:40.934 --> 00:06:42.311
You know what?

159
00:06:42.335 --> 00:06:44.414
I bet it was the engagement.

160
00:06:44.438 --> 00:06:46.983
I've shown I can go all the way.

161
00:06:47.007 --> 00:06:47.984
All the way?

162
00:06:48.008 --> 00:06:49.051
Not our all the way.

163
00:06:49.075 --> 00:06:50.453
Their all the way.

164
00:06:50.477 --> 00:06:52.154
I got the stink of
responsibility on me.

165
00:06:52.178 --> 00:06:54.023
Yeah. you were
engaged for. like. a minute.

166
00:06:54.047 --> 00:06:55.157
I was engaged for a year.

167
00:06:55.181 --> 00:06:57.460
You stink worse than I do.

168
00:06:57.484 --> 00:06:59.362
I'm feeling somethin'
else here. Jerry.

169
00:06:59.386 --> 00:07:01.163
[♪♪♪]

170
00:07:01.187 --> 00:07:03.867
WOMAN [OVER SPEAKER PHONE]:
<i>Elaine. Mr. Peterman on line one.</i>

171
00:07:03.891 --> 00:07:06.569
Hello. Mr. Peterman.
how are you feeling?

172
00:07:06.593 --> 00:07:10.339
Elaine. I'll be blunt.
I'm burnt out. I'm fried.

173
00:07:10.363 --> 00:07:12.964
My mind is as barren as
the surface of the moon.

174
00:07:14.701 --> 00:07:16.613
I can run that
catalogue no longer.

175
00:07:16.637 --> 00:07:18.581
What? Who's gonna do it?

176
00:07:18.605 --> 00:07:19.682
What about you?

177
00:07:19.706 --> 00:07:22.018
Me? Why me?

178
00:07:22.042 --> 00:07:23.708
Why. indeed.

179
00:07:25.278 --> 00:07:27.290
Mr. Peterman. you can't leave.

180
00:07:27.314 --> 00:07:28.758
I've already left. Elaine.

181
00:07:28.782 --> 00:07:30.715
I'm in Burma.

182
00:07:31.785 --> 00:07:32.796
Burma?

183
00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:34.130
[LAUGHS] You most likely

184
00:07:34.154 --> 00:07:35.532
know it as Myanmar.

185
00:07:35.556 --> 00:07:38.367
But it will always
be Burma to me.

186
00:07:38.391 --> 00:07:40.202
Bonne chance.<i> Elaine.</i>

187
00:07:40.226 --> 00:07:45.241
You there. on the motorbike.
sell me one of your melons.

188
00:07:45.265 --> 00:07:46.743
<i>Mr. Peterman?</i>

189
00:07:46.767 --> 00:07:47.744
Where?

190
00:07:47.768 --> 00:07:49.412
Burma.

191
00:07:49.436 --> 00:07:51.113
Isn't it Myanmar now?

192
00:07:51.137 --> 00:07:52.916
Jerry. he wants me
to run the catalogue.

193
00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:55.652
I mean. it's crazy. I
can't be in charge.

194
00:07:55.676 --> 00:07:56.886
No. certainly not.

195
00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:58.387
I mean. I can't
give people orders.

196
00:07:58.411 --> 00:07:59.756
No one's gonna listen to you.

197
00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:02.325
I am not qualified
to run the catalogue.

198
00:08:02.349 --> 00:08:04.829
You're not qualified to
work at the catalogue.

199
00:08:06.587 --> 00:08:07.564
Hey.

200
00:08:07.588 --> 00:08:08.598
[GROANING]

201
00:08:08.622 --> 00:08:09.966
What's wrong?

202
00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:11.634
Oh. Peterman ran off to Burma.

203
00:08:11.658 --> 00:08:13.736
And now he wants
me to run the catalogue.

204
00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:15.839
Where? Myanmar.

205
00:08:15.863 --> 00:08:18.129
Is that the discount pharmacy?

206
00:08:19.466 --> 00:08:21.511
Well. I'm just
gonna tell him no.

207
00:08:21.535 --> 00:08:23.112
I can't run the catalogue.

208
00:08:23.136 --> 00:08:25.414
Whoa. whoa. "can't"?

209
00:08:25.438 --> 00:08:27.984
When did that word
enter your vocabulary?

210
00:08:28.008 --> 00:08:29.752
What. is the job too difficult?

211
00:08:29.776 --> 00:08:33.756
What. you don't have
enough experience?

212
00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:36.225
You're not smart enough?

213
00:08:36.249 --> 00:08:39.061
Where's your confidence?

214
00:08:39.085 --> 00:08:42.031
Elaine. let me tell you a story.

215
00:08:42.055 --> 00:08:44.166
When I first started karate...

216
00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:47.169
"Ka-ra-tay"? Yeah.
I had no support.

217
00:08:47.193 --> 00:08:51.140
Not from him. not
from Newman. no one.

218
00:08:51.164 --> 00:08:54.644
First time I sparred with
an opponent I was terrified.

219
00:08:54.668 --> 00:08:57.647
My legs. they were like noodles.

220
00:08:57.671 --> 00:09:01.384
Then I looked inside.
and I found my katra.

221
00:09:01.408 --> 00:09:02.652
"Katra"?

222
00:09:02.676 --> 00:09:05.054
Yeah. your spirit.
your. uh. being.

223
00:09:05.078 --> 00:09:08.190
That part of you that
says. "Yes. I can."

224
00:09:08.214 --> 00:09:09.915
Sammy Davis had it.

225
00:09:11.484 --> 00:09:14.430
So I listened to
my katra. and now:

226
00:09:14.454 --> 00:09:15.431
[TRUMPETS]

227
00:09:15.455 --> 00:09:16.888
I'm dominating the dojo.

228
00:09:17.891 --> 00:09:19.524
I'm class champion.

229
00:09:21.662 --> 00:09:22.772
Well. you know. I...

230
00:09:22.796 --> 00:09:24.974
I have watched Peterman
run the company.

231
00:09:24.998 --> 00:09:26.075
Sure. you have.

232
00:09:26.099 --> 00:09:27.844
I know how to do it.

233
00:09:27.868 --> 00:09:29.045
Mm-hm.

234
00:09:29.069 --> 00:09:31.548
Pair of pants. stupid
story. a huge markup.

235
00:09:31.572 --> 00:09:33.750
I can do that.

236
00:09:33.774 --> 00:09:36.619
You follow your katra
and you can do anything.

237
00:09:36.643 --> 00:09:37.687
[LAUGHING]

238
00:09:37.711 --> 00:09:39.231
Now get out of here. Okay.

239
00:09:41.615 --> 00:09:43.492
That kid is gonna be all right.

240
00:09:43.516 --> 00:09:45.327
No. she's not. [BANGING ON DOOR]

241
00:09:45.351 --> 00:09:48.097
BOY: Come on. Kramer.

242
00:09:48.121 --> 00:09:49.131
Hey there.

243
00:09:49.155 --> 00:09:51.534
Come on. Mom's down in the car.

244
00:09:51.558 --> 00:09:52.769
Okay. Joey.

245
00:09:52.793 --> 00:09:54.370
You guys have class
at the same time?

246
00:09:54.394 --> 00:09:56.673
No. we're in the same class.

247
00:09:56.697 --> 00:09:58.207
You're in the same class?

248
00:09:58.231 --> 00:10:00.509
He almost beat me.

249
00:10:00.533 --> 00:10:02.845
Kramer. you're
fighting children?

250
00:10:02.869 --> 00:10:06.749
We're all at the
same skill level. Jerry.

251
00:10:06.773 --> 00:10:08.451
He's 9 years old.

252
00:10:08.475 --> 00:10:11.387
You don't need karate.
You can just ring his neck.

253
00:10:11.411 --> 00:10:12.622
[CAR HORN HONKING]

254
00:10:12.646 --> 00:10:14.724
I got car pool.

255
00:10:14.748 --> 00:10:16.025
[♪♪♪]

256
00:10:16.049 --> 00:10:18.127
KRAMER: Thanks for
the juice box. Mrs. Z.

257
00:10:18.151 --> 00:10:20.797
Hey. can we stop for ice
cream on the way home. Mom?

258
00:10:20.821 --> 00:10:22.198
Mmm. I don't know about...

259
00:10:22.222 --> 00:10:24.266
ALL: Please!

260
00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:26.869
Please. please!

261
00:10:26.893 --> 00:10:27.904
All right.

262
00:10:27.928 --> 00:10:29.371
ALL: Yeah!

263
00:10:29.395 --> 00:10:31.240
[♪♪♪]

264
00:10:31.264 --> 00:10:32.875
DUGAN: You're taking the job?

265
00:10:32.899 --> 00:10:34.577
You got that straight.

266
00:10:34.601 --> 00:10:37.546
Now. I want four new ideas
from each of you by 6:00.

267
00:10:37.570 --> 00:10:39.716
No. make that six ideas by 4:00.

268
00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:43.174
All right. Let's move.
Move! Move! Move! Move!

269
00:10:47.313 --> 00:10:48.791
Are you prepared for kumite?

270
00:10:48.815 --> 00:10:50.159
BOTH: Yes. sensei.

271
00:10:50.183 --> 00:10:52.061
Fighting stance.

272
00:10:52.085 --> 00:10:54.597
[BOTH GRUNT] Begin!

273
00:10:54.621 --> 00:10:55.732
Ha-ya-ya-ya-ya-ya-ya!

274
00:10:55.756 --> 00:10:57.066
[♪♪♪]

275
00:10:57.090 --> 00:10:58.957
[YELLING AND GRUNTING]

276
00:11:06.432 --> 00:11:08.066
[SCREAMING]

277
00:11:09.302 --> 00:11:10.747
[KRAMER YELLING]

278
00:11:10.771 --> 00:11:12.314
<i>[GONG BONGS]</i>

279
00:11:12.338 --> 00:11:14.050
Winner.

280
00:11:14.074 --> 00:11:16.252
[♪♪♪]

281
00:11:16.276 --> 00:11:18.420
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

282
00:11:18.444 --> 00:11:20.378
It's open.

283
00:11:23.784 --> 00:11:24.761
Rosses.

284
00:11:24.785 --> 00:11:25.762
Hello. George.

285
00:11:25.786 --> 00:11:29.165
[STAMMERING] Come in. Come in.

286
00:11:29.189 --> 00:11:31.400
We. uh. tried to call.
but the line was busy.

287
00:11:31.424 --> 00:11:33.803
Oh. oh. yeah. Sure. here.

288
00:11:33.827 --> 00:11:35.838
Uh. sit down. please.

289
00:11:35.862 --> 00:11:37.774
Uh... Uh. cheese there?

290
00:11:37.798 --> 00:11:41.343
We know the last three
months have been hard on you.

291
00:11:41.367 --> 00:11:44.480
Oh. yes. yes. yes.
Very. very hard.

292
00:11:44.504 --> 00:11:47.116
And they've been hard on us too.

293
00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:48.317
It's a terrible tragedy

294
00:11:48.341 --> 00:11:50.452
when parents
outlive their children.

295
00:11:50.476 --> 00:11:55.524
Yes. I agree. I... I hope my
parents go long before I do.

296
00:11:55.548 --> 00:11:58.761
That's why we decided
to create a foundation

297
00:11:58.785 --> 00:12:01.164
to preserve Susan's memory.

298
00:12:01.188 --> 00:12:03.632
Oh. that's wonderful.

299
00:12:03.656 --> 00:12:06.569
And. of course. we want
you to be an integral part.

300
00:12:06.593 --> 00:12:09.238
Yes. integ...

301
00:12:09.262 --> 00:12:11.674
H-how int...? How integral?

302
00:12:11.698 --> 00:12:13.509
You'll be on the
board of directors.

303
00:12:13.533 --> 00:12:14.911
Great.

304
00:12:14.935 --> 00:12:16.913
[CHUCKLING] Great!

305
00:12:16.937 --> 00:12:21.050
Oh. oh. oh. gosh.
you know. it's just...

306
00:12:21.074 --> 00:12:22.719
My duties with the
Yankees. you know...

307
00:12:22.743 --> 00:12:25.054
MRS. ROSS: Oh.
don't worry. George.

308
00:12:25.078 --> 00:12:28.324
The foundation will revolve
around your schedule.

309
00:12:28.348 --> 00:12:32.617
Evening. weekends.
whenever you have free time.

310
00:12:34.387 --> 00:12:36.999
I can't believe
this is happening.

311
00:12:37.023 --> 00:12:39.202
Well. it wouldn't have
without your friend Jerry's

312
00:12:39.226 --> 00:12:41.771
inspirational words.

313
00:12:41.795 --> 00:12:45.908
He said to us. "She's not
really dead if her shadow is..."

314
00:12:45.932 --> 00:12:48.577
Uh. what was it. dear?

315
00:12:48.601 --> 00:12:50.346
Something about
a way. wasn't it?

316
00:12:50.370 --> 00:12:52.949
And a light and a...

317
00:12:52.973 --> 00:12:54.083
[CHUCKLES]

318
00:12:54.107 --> 00:12:56.418
Who the hell knows.

319
00:12:56.442 --> 00:12:59.555
MR. ROSS: But what's important
is that your relationship with Susan

320
00:12:59.579 --> 00:13:01.023
doesn't have to end.

321
00:13:01.047 --> 00:13:04.593
MRS. ROSS: So will you
be sure to thank Jerry for us?

322
00:13:04.617 --> 00:13:07.096
The second I see him.

323
00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:08.319
[♪♪♪]

324
00:13:11.324 --> 00:13:13.191
[♪♪♪]

325
00:13:17.330 --> 00:13:18.307
Hey.

326
00:13:18.331 --> 00:13:20.209
Hey.

327
00:13:20.233 --> 00:13:21.543
How's your day? Good?

328
00:13:21.567 --> 00:13:22.745
Actually. yeah.

329
00:13:22.769 --> 00:13:24.881
I'm meeting Mulva
here in a few minutes.

330
00:13:24.905 --> 00:13:26.949
So. uh...

331
00:13:26.973 --> 00:13:28.217
<i>Wrath of Khan.</i> huh?

332
00:13:28.241 --> 00:13:30.522
Yeah. was that a beauty or what?

333
00:13:32.078 --> 00:13:33.256
What was that line again?

334
00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:37.260
Something about... finding
your way in a shadow?

335
00:13:37.284 --> 00:13:38.961
No. no. no. it's.
"She's not really dead

336
00:13:38.985 --> 00:13:41.330
if we find a way
to remember her."

337
00:13:41.354 --> 00:13:42.731
That's it.

338
00:13:42.755 --> 00:13:45.467
That's the line...

339
00:13:45.491 --> 00:13:47.892
that destroyed my life.

340
00:13:51.497 --> 00:13:53.075
Problem?

341
00:13:53.099 --> 00:13:55.344
The Rosses have started
up a foundation. Jerry.

342
00:13:55.368 --> 00:13:57.613
and I have to sit on
the board of directors.

343
00:13:57.637 --> 00:13:59.782
Hey. board of
directors. look at you.

344
00:13:59.806 --> 00:14:03.052
Yeah. look at me. I
was free and clear.

345
00:14:03.076 --> 00:14:05.487
I was living the dream. I
was stripped to the waist

346
00:14:05.511 --> 00:14:08.825
eating a block of cheese
the size of a car battery.

347
00:14:08.849 --> 00:14:10.993
Before we go any further.
I'd just like to point out

348
00:14:11.017 --> 00:14:14.663
how disturbing it is that you
equate eating a block of cheese

349
00:14:14.687 --> 00:14:17.433
with some sort of
bachelor paradise.

350
00:14:17.457 --> 00:14:20.203
Don't you see? I'm back in.

351
00:14:20.227 --> 00:14:22.604
All because of<i>
Wrath of Khan?</i> Yes!

352
00:14:22.628 --> 00:14:25.108
Well. it was the
best of those movies.

353
00:14:27.033 --> 00:14:31.914
Khan!

354
00:14:31.938 --> 00:14:34.472
[♪♪♪]

355
00:14:37.344 --> 00:14:38.442
George?

356
00:14:41.147 --> 00:14:43.059
George? Oh!

357
00:14:43.083 --> 00:14:46.495
I'm Wyck Thayer. chairman
of the Susan Ross Foundation.

358
00:14:46.519 --> 00:14:47.496
Wink?

359
00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:49.999
Wyck. Wyck.

360
00:14:50.023 --> 00:14:53.236
Now. as you know. the. uh.
Rosses had considerable monies.

361
00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:55.738
Well. I... I know they
have some monies.

362
00:14:55.762 --> 00:14:58.997
They had more than some
monies. Many. many monies.

363
00:15:00.767 --> 00:15:03.412
And they planned. uh.
to give a sizable portion

364
00:15:03.436 --> 00:15:06.582
of their estate to you and
Susan after the wedding.

365
00:15:06.606 --> 00:15:09.718
So if Susan and I had...

366
00:15:09.742 --> 00:15:13.555
I mean. if the
envelopes hadn't. uh...

367
00:15:13.579 --> 00:15:14.857
Then we...

368
00:15:14.881 --> 00:15:15.925
Yes.

369
00:15:15.949 --> 00:15:16.926
And now?

370
00:15:16.950 --> 00:15:18.627
Not.

371
00:15:18.651 --> 00:15:21.430
It's all been endowed
to the foundation.

372
00:15:21.454 --> 00:15:22.999
Even this townhouse.

373
00:15:23.023 --> 00:15:24.566
This townhouse?

374
00:15:24.590 --> 00:15:26.903
Yes. this would have
been your wedding gift.

375
00:15:26.927 --> 00:15:28.371
And now? Not.

376
00:15:28.395 --> 00:15:30.506
Not.

377
00:15:30.530 --> 00:15:34.210
Also endowed.

378
00:15:34.234 --> 00:15:37.579
George. I know how
much Susan meant to you.

379
00:15:37.603 --> 00:15:38.680
This can't be easy.

380
00:15:38.704 --> 00:15:40.482
You know. it really can't.

381
00:15:40.506 --> 00:15:43.052
[♪♪♪]

382
00:15:43.076 --> 00:15:44.453
DOLORES: So who broke it off?

383
00:15:44.477 --> 00:15:46.222
Well. that's the
thing. It was mutual.

384
00:15:46.246 --> 00:15:48.724
Oh. come on. Everybody
knows there's no such thing

385
00:15:48.748 --> 00:15:51.693
as a mutual breakup.
Tell me the truth.

386
00:15:51.717 --> 00:15:54.263
I am. It was the world's first.

387
00:15:54.287 --> 00:15:55.298
[SIGHS]

388
00:15:55.322 --> 00:15:56.966
You know. when I
heard you got engaged.

389
00:15:56.990 --> 00:15:58.434
I thought maybe you'd matured.

390
00:15:58.458 --> 00:16:01.037
but obviously there's
no growth here.

391
00:16:01.061 --> 00:16:02.871
Well. I can't argue with that.

392
00:16:02.895 --> 00:16:05.207
but the fact remains
I was completely...

393
00:16:05.231 --> 00:16:07.543
Mulva.

394
00:16:07.567 --> 00:16:09.245
[RINGING]

395
00:16:09.269 --> 00:16:10.868
[LOCKS TURNING]

396
00:16:17.844 --> 00:16:19.188
Hello.

397
00:16:19.212 --> 00:16:21.357
WOMAN [OVER PHONE]:
<i>Please hold for Elaine Benes.</i>

398
00:16:21.381 --> 00:16:23.914
Oh. I don't believe this.

399
00:16:24.750 --> 00:16:26.128
Jerry?

400
00:16:26.152 --> 00:16:27.430
JERRY: <i>Hey.</i>

401
00:16:27.454 --> 00:16:31.400
Hey. guess who just finished
laying out her first issue

402
00:16:31.424 --> 00:16:33.402
of the J. Peterman Catalogue?

403
00:16:33.426 --> 00:16:34.403
How's it look?

404
00:16:34.427 --> 00:16:35.704
It's a peach.

405
00:16:35.728 --> 00:16:38.574
<i>What's that?</i> I
say. it's a peach.

406
00:16:38.598 --> 00:16:39.775
Let me ask you something.

407
00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:41.677
When I told you my
breakup was mutual.

408
00:16:41.701 --> 00:16:43.612
did you believe me? No. no. no.

409
00:16:43.636 --> 00:16:45.014
It's weak. No
one's gonna buy it.

410
00:16:45.038 --> 00:16:47.183
and you shouldn't be selling it.

411
00:16:47.207 --> 00:16:49.585
I gotta do some research here.

412
00:16:49.609 --> 00:16:52.276
Hey. hey. Me. talkin'?

413
00:16:53.613 --> 00:16:54.923
<i>You know.</i>

414
00:16:54.947 --> 00:16:56.993
between you and me.

415
00:16:57.017 --> 00:17:01.197
I always thought Kramer
was a bit of a doofus.

416
00:17:01.221 --> 00:17:03.966
But he believed in me.

417
00:17:03.990 --> 00:17:05.368
You did not.

418
00:17:05.392 --> 00:17:08.837
So as I see it.
he's not the doofus.

419
00:17:08.861 --> 00:17:11.107
you are the doofus.

420
00:17:11.131 --> 00:17:12.141
Oh. I'm the doofus?

421
00:17:12.165 --> 00:17:13.209
<i>Yes.</i>

422
00:17:13.233 --> 00:17:16.979
You. Jerry. are the doofus.

423
00:17:17.003 --> 00:17:18.114
You know. it occurs to me

424
00:17:18.138 --> 00:17:20.883
that Kramer is at
"ka-ra-tay" right now.

425
00:17:20.907 --> 00:17:22.385
Well. maybe I'll
just go down there

426
00:17:22.409 --> 00:17:24.186
and thank him in person.

427
00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:26.422
Yeah. that's what
I was thinkin'.

428
00:17:26.446 --> 00:17:29.058
[♪♪♪]

429
00:17:29.082 --> 00:17:30.459
[YELLING]

430
00:17:30.483 --> 00:17:32.228
Kramer?

431
00:17:32.252 --> 00:17:34.130
Ahh!

432
00:17:34.154 --> 00:17:35.631
Oh. hey. What are you doing?

433
00:17:35.655 --> 00:17:38.156
Oh. well. I'm dom...
I'm dominating.

434
00:17:39.426 --> 00:17:41.303
You never said you
were fighting children.

435
00:17:41.327 --> 00:17:44.507
Well. it's not the size
of the opponent. Elaine.

436
00:17:44.531 --> 00:17:46.975
It's. uh... the ferocity.

437
00:17:46.999 --> 00:17:49.778
This is what you
used to build me up?

438
00:17:49.802 --> 00:17:52.548
This is where got all
that stupid katra stuff?

439
00:17:52.572 --> 00:17:56.152
No. no. no. that's
from. uh.<i> Star Trek III.</i>

440
00:17:56.176 --> 00:17:57.819
<i>The Search for Spock.</i>

441
00:17:57.843 --> 00:18:00.423
<i>Search for Spock?</i>

442
00:18:00.447 --> 00:18:03.426
Yeah. yeah. I know. Jerry will
tell you that the<i> Wrath of Khan</i>

443
00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:05.894
is the better picture.
but for me. I...

444
00:18:05.918 --> 00:18:06.918
You doofus!

445
00:18:08.521 --> 00:18:10.166
CHILDREN: Wow.

446
00:18:10.190 --> 00:18:13.569
[♪♪♪]

447
00:18:13.593 --> 00:18:15.104
Okay. question number eight:

448
00:18:15.128 --> 00:18:18.541
what if I told you my fiancée
left me for another man?

449
00:18:18.565 --> 00:18:21.877
Does that make me more
likable. less likable. as likable?

450
00:18:21.901 --> 00:18:23.512
Let's start over here this time.

451
00:18:23.536 --> 00:18:25.414
More.

452
00:18:25.438 --> 00:18:26.748
Less.

453
00:18:26.772 --> 00:18:28.717
Same.

454
00:18:28.741 --> 00:18:30.641
Are we about through here?

455
00:18:32.979 --> 00:18:35.924
[♪♪♪]

456
00:18:35.948 --> 00:18:38.694
I thought you said your mom
was meeting us in the alley.

457
00:18:38.718 --> 00:18:42.131
Ah. she had a little
change of plans.

458
00:18:42.155 --> 00:18:44.032
[♪♪♪]

459
00:18:44.056 --> 00:18:45.934
What's going on?

460
00:18:45.958 --> 00:18:47.903
Hey. Timmy. Clara.

461
00:18:47.927 --> 00:18:51.140
That was some kind of
workout we had tonight. huh?

462
00:18:51.164 --> 00:18:52.941
Now we finish it.

463
00:18:52.965 --> 00:18:54.577
Huh? Wha...?

464
00:18:54.601 --> 00:18:56.011
BOY: Get him.

465
00:18:56.035 --> 00:18:58.947
Ah! Ahh! Mama!

466
00:18:58.971 --> 00:19:01.317
[♪♪♪]

467
00:19:01.341 --> 00:19:02.985
JERRY: Dad. I
wouldn't eat anything

468
00:19:03.009 --> 00:19:06.388
you caught in that pond
out in front of the condo.

469
00:19:06.412 --> 00:19:09.592
All right. Look. Elaine's
here. I gotta get going.

470
00:19:09.616 --> 00:19:11.393
Uh. by the way. uh...

471
00:19:11.417 --> 00:19:14.296
I'm not getting
married. Tell Mom. Bye.

472
00:19:14.320 --> 00:19:18.167
[PHONE RINGS]

473
00:19:18.191 --> 00:19:19.823
So...

474
00:19:21.961 --> 00:19:23.839
Did you stop by the dojo?

475
00:19:23.863 --> 00:19:25.007
Yup.

476
00:19:25.031 --> 00:19:26.575
How's your confidence level?

477
00:19:26.599 --> 00:19:27.576
Shot.

478
00:19:27.600 --> 00:19:28.910
Self-esteem?

479
00:19:28.934 --> 00:19:30.613
Gone. Doofus?

480
00:19:30.637 --> 00:19:32.848
Yo.

481
00:19:32.872 --> 00:19:34.750
All right. So what?

482
00:19:34.774 --> 00:19:37.475
You put out the catalogue.
How bad could it be?

483
00:19:44.584 --> 00:19:46.162
What is that?

484
00:19:46.186 --> 00:19:49.865
The urban sombrero.

485
00:19:49.889 --> 00:19:51.600
I put it on the cover.

486
00:19:51.624 --> 00:19:55.560
Well. nobody sees the... cover.

487
00:19:57.463 --> 00:19:58.807
What happened to you?

488
00:19:58.831 --> 00:20:01.109
Whew. I got whupped.

489
00:20:01.133 --> 00:20:03.945
You should have seen
the rage in their little eyes.

490
00:20:03.969 --> 00:20:07.749
And those tiny
little fists of fury.

491
00:20:07.773 --> 00:20:08.773
Oh.

492
00:20:10.142 --> 00:20:11.853
What is that?

493
00:20:11.877 --> 00:20:15.023
It's the new cover of the
J. Peterman catalogue.

494
00:20:15.047 --> 00:20:16.892
It is Elaine's choice.

495
00:20:16.916 --> 00:20:18.216
Let's congratulate her.

496
00:20:19.285 --> 00:20:20.496
Whoa.

497
00:20:20.520 --> 00:20:22.631
This is all your fault.

498
00:20:22.655 --> 00:20:24.800
You told me I could
run the company.

499
00:20:24.824 --> 00:20:28.036
Well. then I was way off!

500
00:20:28.060 --> 00:20:30.239
Well. I'll see ya.

501
00:20:30.263 --> 00:20:32.463
<i>Vaya con Dios.</i>

502
00:20:34.100 --> 00:20:36.111
Man. I gotta go lay down.

503
00:20:36.135 --> 00:20:37.979
Are you and George
going out a little later?

504
00:20:38.003 --> 00:20:39.815
No. he's still stuck
at the foundation.

505
00:20:39.839 --> 00:20:41.983
You know. you oughta go
down there and help him out.

506
00:20:42.007 --> 00:20:43.151
He's a widower.

507
00:20:43.175 --> 00:20:46.888
Widower? Wait a second.

508
00:20:46.912 --> 00:20:48.090
[♪♪♪]

509
00:20:48.114 --> 00:20:51.827
Okay. let's see. The
beach house. 48 acres...

510
00:20:51.851 --> 00:20:53.028
Ooh. Southampton.

511
00:20:53.052 --> 00:20:54.863
That should fetch a fair price.

512
00:20:54.887 --> 00:20:57.199
Would I have had access to that?

513
00:20:57.223 --> 00:20:58.667
Course. Would have been yours.

514
00:20:58.691 --> 00:21:00.336
And now?

515
00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:01.570
Not.

516
00:21:01.594 --> 00:21:02.571
[PHONE RINGS]

517
00:21:02.595 --> 00:21:03.628
Got it.

518
00:21:07.967 --> 00:21:08.944
Hello.

519
00:21:08.968 --> 00:21:10.279
JERRY: <i>Hey. Georgie.</i>

520
00:21:10.303 --> 00:21:12.348
I'm doing some research
down at the coffee shop.

521
00:21:12.372 --> 00:21:13.915
Your story's the one.

522
00:21:13.939 --> 00:21:16.118
My story? Yeah.
your widower story's

523
00:21:16.142 --> 00:21:17.375
tested through the roof.

524
00:21:19.612 --> 00:21:21.223
When are you
getting out of there?

525
00:21:21.247 --> 00:21:25.294
Um. Excuse me. Wyck. are
we. uh. almost done here?

526
00:21:25.318 --> 00:21:27.785
[CHUCKLING] No.
no. not even close.

527
00:21:33.459 --> 00:21:34.870
I can't go.

528
00:21:34.894 --> 00:21:36.705
What do you mean. you can't go?

529
00:21:36.729 --> 00:21:39.007
There's two really cute
girls sitting at the counter.

530
00:21:39.031 --> 00:21:40.309
eating grilled cheese.

531
00:21:40.333 --> 00:21:41.410
Cheese. George.

532
00:21:41.434 --> 00:21:43.945
<i>Cheese.</i>

533
00:21:43.969 --> 00:21:47.383
Okay. next item.
Susan's doll collection.

534
00:21:47.407 --> 00:21:51.086
Estimated value: 2.6 million.

535
00:21:51.110 --> 00:21:54.356
What do you say we go
through this doll by doll.

536
00:21:54.380 --> 00:21:56.246
[♪♪♪]

537
00:22:10.730 --> 00:22:12.408
It was nothing unusual.

538
00:22:12.432 --> 00:22:14.777
Every afternoon
for the last 24 years.

539
00:22:14.801 --> 00:22:17.746
I'd shut the door to my office
and sneak a little shuteye.

540
00:22:17.770 --> 00:22:19.415
No one was the wiser.

541
00:22:19.439 --> 00:22:23.919
But then my wife gets
me this urban sombrero.

542
00:22:23.943 --> 00:22:27.088
The next thing I know.
my ass is out on the street.

543
00:22:27.112 --> 00:22:29.057
I tried one too.

544
00:22:29.081 --> 00:22:32.294
I woke up and found my
walking papers tacked to the brim.

545
00:22:32.318 --> 00:22:34.418
Stupid J. Pendleton.

546
00:22:35.221 --> 00:22:37.633
It's "Peterman."

547
00:22:37.657 --> 00:22:40.769
It's J. Peterman.

548
00:22:40.793 --> 00:22:43.905
I never thought a hat
would destroy my life.

549
00:22:43.929 --> 00:22:45.796
[♪♪♪]

549
